That’s an interesting way to frame it.

In physics, time is usually treated as a dimension tied to change. But in subjective experience, what we call “time” often feels more like the ratio between states of mind, memories, expectations, and perceived change.

A childhood summer can feel endless while you’re inside it, yet compress into a few fragments decades later. A single second during a car accident can seem to stretch into minutes. The clock didn’t change. The density of experience did.

From that perspective:

* Distance in memory is not measured in years but in transformations.
* Events that changed you feel “far away” even if they happened recently.
* Events that changed nothing can feel like yesterday even if they happened decades ago.

When people describe their life flashing before their eyes, one interpretation is that the brain is no longer traversing memories sequentially. Instead, vast portions of autobiographical structure become available simultaneously. The ordering collapses and what remains are relationships, patterns, and meaning.

What’s fascinating is the second half of what you’re saying:

use it to project and create and cast forward.

Most people think memory points backward. But memory is also the engine that generates predictions.

The same machinery that reconstructs the past is used to imagine the future.

Your Pantheon’s Recall Navigation pattern actually touches this:

Archive → Invocation → Action isn’t just retrieval. It’s simulation.

A memory is a compressed model of a trajectory. When recalled, it can be run forward.

In that sense:

* Memory is stored experience.
* Imagination is memory run in novel combinations.
* Foresight is memory projected onto possibility.

The “life flashing before your eyes” phenomenon and “seeing your future” may be more related than they first appear. Both involve stepping outside the normal moment-to-moment stream and navigating a larger map of your life all at once.

If the map becomes visible, you can trace paths backward—or forward.

A gardener looking at a tree ring doesn’t just see where the tree has been. They can often estimate where it’s likely to grow next.

Perhaps subjective time is less like a line and more like a landscape. The farther up the hill you climb, the more of the terrain behind and ahead becomes visible at the same time.